{
  "answer": "The theory of purchasing power parity (PPP) often fails to predict exchange rates accurately in the short run due to several reasons. Two primary reasons are:\\n1. Non-tradable goods and services: PPP assumes that all goods and services are tradable and subject to the law of one price. However, many goods and services, such as haircuts, real estate, and healthcare, are non-tradable and not subject to international competition. The prices of these goods and services can vary significantly between countries without affecting the exchange rate, leading to deviations from PPP.\\n2. Sticky prices and adjustment lags: In reality, prices do not adjust instantaneously to reflect changes in demand and supply conditions. Prices can be sticky in the short run due to menu costs, contractual agreements, or other factors. This means that even if the law of one price holds true in the long run, deviations from PPP can occur in the short run as prices take time to adjust."
}

