{
  "answer": "Step 1: In consumer theory, preferences over consumption bundles are often represented by utility functions. Convexity of preferences implies that a consumer prefers mixtures of two bundles at least as much as either of the pure bundles. This is captured by Definition A.17, which defines a set as convex if for any two points in the set, all convex combinations of these points also lie in the set.\\nStep 2: The separating hyperplane theorem (Theorem A.8) states that if two sets A and B are disjoint and convex, there exists a hyperplane H(p,c) that separates them. This means that all points in A lie on one side of the hyperplane, and all points in B lie on the opposite side.\\nStep 3: In the context of consumer theory, this theorem can be used to separate two sets of consumption bundles. For example, let A represent the set of affordable bundles for a consumer given prices p and income m, and B represent the set of preferred bundles to the chosen bundle. Since both A and B are typically convex, the separating hyperplane theorem guarantees the existence of a hyperplane that separates these two sets.\\nStep 4: The economic interpretation of this separation is that there exists a price vector p and a level of income m such that the consumer's chosen bundle lies on the budget line (the hyperplane), while all other affordable but less preferred bundles lie below the budget line, and all more preferred but unaffordable bundles lie above the budget line."
