{
  "answer": "In nonparametric regression, the tradeoff between approximation error ($a_n$) and estimation error ($\\epsilon_n$) is influenced by the choice of $\\kappa(n)$, which determines the complexity of the function space $C_{\\kappa(n)}$. \\\\(Step 1:\\) As $\\kappa(n)$ increases, the function space becomes richer, potentially reducing the approximation error $a_n$ because the true regression function $f^*$ can be better approximated by elements in $C_{\\kappa(n)}$. \\\\(Step 2:\\) However, increasing $\\kappa(n)$ also leads to a larger estimation error $\\epsilon_n$, since estimating more parameters from a finite sample size $n$ becomes more challenging, especially when the signal-to-noise ratio is low. \\\\(Step 3:\\) The optimal choice of $\\kappa(n)$ balances these two errors. If $\\kappa(n)/n \\rightarrow 0$, the sequence of function spaces $C_{\\kappa(n)}$ is dense in $L^2(X)$, ensuring that $f^*$ can be well-approximated as $n$ grows. Under these conditions, the combined effect of $\\epsilon_n + a_n$ converges at a rate that approaches the parametric rate, indicating an effective balance between approximation and estimation errors."
